decision_conditions:
Condition : 1 - Details of restoration works to Hanworth Park House

Prior to the commencement of the development on the house itself (not including demolition, vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved drawings), details of the following matters regarding Hanworth Park House shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority that include:

a)	Large scale details of all external joinery including wooden-framed glazing (1:50 elevation, 1:20 section) including vertical and horizontal cross-sections through openings to show the positions of joinery within openings, depth of reveal, heads, sills and lintels;
b)	Large scale details of all internal joinery (1:5 elevation, 1:2 section);
c)	Full details of proposed rooflights, which shall be set in plane with the roof covering;
d)	Full details of external flues, background and mechanical ventilation, soil/vent pipes and their exits to the open air;
e)	Full details of proposed meter and alarm boxes;
f)	Full details of proposed internal service routes;
g)	A full schedule and specification of repairs including:
i.	Proposed method of cleaning/paint removal from historic fabric;
ii.	A full schedule of internal finishes to walls, ceilings and floors;
iii.	Full details of external decoration to joinery and metalwork; and
iv.	Full details and samples of external materials.

The works shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details.

Reason: In the interests of preserving the character and appearance of the listed building and its setting, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021). 
Condition : 2 - 2.	Schedule of all features to be removed, moved, replaced or reinstated

Prior to the commencement of the development, (not including any vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved
Drawings), a schedule of all features to be removed, moved, replaced or reinstated shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.

All replacement and reinstatement features must match the original in materials and detail. Photographs/drawings/sections recording the features to be replicated must be submitted along with 1:1 scale drawings of proposed items for approval by the Local Planning Authority.

Reason: To ensure the satisfactory preservation of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 3 - Building Recording

Prior to the commencement of the development, (not including any vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved
Drawings), details of the extent of removal of original fabric has been agreed in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The fabric in question to be removed/ demolished must be fully recorded by scaled drawing and photographs and these records passed to the Local Planning Authority prior to removal/demolition of the item (as per relevant building recording conditions applied to individual buildings above).

Reason: In order to provide a reasonable opportunity to record the history of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 4 - Acoustic/Thermal insulation and fire precautions

Prior to the commencement of the development, including any demolition, vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved drawings, full details of any acoustic/thermal insulation and overarching fire precautions works to demonstrate their effect on the character and appearance of the listed building shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority and the development shall be carried out in complete accordance with the detail so approved. 
Consideration should be given to draught exclusion measures and secondary glazing. 

Reason: In the interests of the architectural and historic integrity of the Listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 5 - Approval limited to Drawings

Such an approval is limited to the works shown on the approved drawings and does not indicate approval for associated or enabling works that may be necessary to carry out the scheme. Any further works must be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any works commencing.

Reason: To ensure the satisfactory preservation of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan
(2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 6 - Fire Precaution works � Alarm System

The smoke detectors, fire alarm call points, fire alarms, emergency lighting fittings and control boxes shall be located in unobtrusive positions in the corners of rooms and their electrical cabling systems shall not be surface mounted but concealed within the floors, ceilings and walls, except where otherwise approved, and the walls, floors and ceilings made good to the satisfaction of the Local Planning Authority.

Reason: To ensure the satisfactory preservation of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 7 - Fireproofing details

Prior to the commencement of the development, (not including any vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved
Drawings), details of the method of fire protection of the walls, floors, ceilings and doors, including 1:5 scale sections through walls and ceilings, 1:20 scale elevations of doors and 1:1 scale moulding sections, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. All existing original doors shall be retained unless it is demonstrated that they require replacing and where they are required to be upgraded to meet fire regulations details of upgrading works shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The works shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details.

Reason: To ensure the satisfactory preservation of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021). 
Condition : 8 - Mortar and Repointing

A. Prior to the commencement of the development, (not including any demolition, vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved drawings), a detailed specification of the proposed mortar mix shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The development shall be carried out using the approved specification.

B. Prior to the commencement of the development, (not including any demolition, vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved drawings), details of the extent of repointing and an unobtrusive sample area of brick / stonework etc has been repointed first and the colour, texture and finish shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The development shall be carried out using the approved details.

Reason: To ensure that the proposed works can be effected without detriment to the special architectural and historic interest of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 9 - Details and Samples of Materials

Prior to the commencement of the development, (not including any demolition, vegetation clearance and site preparation, and notwithstanding the approved drawings), details and samples of the materials (including colour of render, paintwork and colourwash) to be used in the construction of the external and internal surfaces of the works hereby permitted shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The works shall be carried out in strict accordance with the approved details.

Reason: To ensure the satisfactory preservation of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 10 - Bats or Birds

No works shall be commenced unless evidence has been provided to the Local Planning Authority that no bats or birds are roosting within Hanworth Park House. If a roost is confirmed then works must proceed under a license issued by Natural England.

Reason: to ensure that bats and their roost are not damaged, destroyed or disturbed by development works and to enable the Local Authority to fulfil its obligation under the Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations (2010) and the Wildlife & Countryside Act (1981).
Condition : 11 - Repair of dilapidated buildings

A. Survey: Given the long-term vacancy of Hanworth Park House, the current state of the building is unknown, but expected to be in relatively advanced dilapidation internally. This affects the information provided on future use. No works shall take place until a full Structural Condition Survey for the building has been carried out to include assessment of all features including, but not limited to, internal finishes, internal joinery fixtures and fittings, ceiling and floor joists, asphalt and cement roofs, rainwater goods, ironmongery, windows, doors, brickwork, other stonework, staircases, internal partitions, utilities wiring and pipework, security and fire precautions and accessibility reasonable adjustments and asbestos mitigation have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, in conjunction with Historic England. 

B. Repair: Following the Structural Condition Survey in Part A, a Method Statement for the works of repair to Hanworth Park House, detailing urgent works (and a timetable for completion), schedules of long-term internal and external repairs and specification and samples of proposed materials to be used in said repairs shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, in conjunction with Historic England. The repair works shall be carried out in strict accordance with the approved Method Statement and further reports and material and mortar conditions may be applied to further discharge this condition as further investigation of the building takes place and plans for the building become clearer.

Reason: To ensure the satisfactory preservation of the listed building, in accordance with Local Plan (2015) policies CC1 and CC2 and London Plan (2021) policy HC1, coupled with the requirements of the National Planning Policy Framework (2021).
Condition : 12 - Conservation Management and Action Plan

Prior to the occupation of the development, a Conservation Management and Action Plan (CMAP), which sets out the ongoing actions necessary to sustain the significance of the listed building during and after works to restore and reuse the building, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority, in conjunction with Historic England. 

In particular, the CMAP shall identify and include:
i.	who will be responsible for the long-term management of the listed building;
ii.	who has responsibility for the actions proposed;
iii.	possible sources of funding for the implementation of the plan, with any time restrictions on expenditure;
iv.	a section setting out the timescale for its implementation and who is responsible for each activity. Timescales should be realistic and take account, where relevant, of the need to apply for grants and obtain any necessary statutory consents;
v.	the necessary repair and maintenance tasks and the frequency with which they will be undertaken.;
vi.	repairs needed to any structure, finishes and contents, setting out priorities and categorising them as Urgent, Necessary and Desirable, as appropriate;
vii.	actions required to conserve or restore the setting of the site;
viii.	an ongoing maintenance schedule;
ix.	provision or retention of public access, and its promotion;
x.	enhancement of the presentation of the site to improve public understanding and enjoyment;
xi.	creation of a framework for site management and any future interventions;
xii.	recording of change, and the maintenance of an archival resource;
xiii.	how future maintenance will be funded in the long term;
xiv.	routine building maintenance schedule, to include:
a.	Clearing leaves, snow, controlling plant growth, removal of bird soiling, inspecting for insect or fungal attack. Removal of graffiti;
